Probably the best reason to hate it is if you didn&#x27;t include the right headers and malloc is therefore implicitly defined to return int.  That creates a bug on most 64-bit compilers where int is 32 bits.  The cast will mask the bug.<p>But more stylistically, let&#x27;s be honest, something like this is way too verbose:<p><pre><code>    struct foo *bar = (struct foo*)malloc(sizeof(struct foo));
</code></pre>
I see code like this often, and I think the only explanation I can think of is that people don&#x27;t know the language well enough to write:<p><pre><code>    struct foo *bar = malloc(sizeof(*bar));
</code></pre>
> A related question is why do people use malloc if calloc is available?<p>Seems like a very different question...  calloc multiplies, calls malloc, and zeros.  I guess if you don&#x27;t want to multiply, don&#x27;t want to zero, don&#x27;t want to bother specifying another parameter, some combination of these, then malloc might be a better choice.  Though I do recall a few years back the OpenBSD folks (possibly others too?) focusing on making sure calloc checks for overflow when it multiplies.  [See also: reallocarray]
